{
    "level": "A2–B1",
    "intro": "In this topic you will learn to recognize <strong>stative verbs</strong> — verbs that describe a <strong>state</strong>, not an active action.",
    "rules": [
        {
            "label": "STATE, NOT ACTION",
            "color": "emerald",
            "text": "Stative verbs talk about opinion, feeling, possession, perception, or state.",
            "example": "know, believe, own, love, seem"
        },
        {
            "label": "USUALLY NOT CONTINUOUS",
            "color": "blue",
            "text": "These verbs <strong>usually do not go in Continuous</strong>.",
            "example": "I know the answer. not I am knowing the answer."
        },
        {
            "label": "SOME VERBS CHANGE MEANING",
            "color": "amber",
            "text": "Some verbs can be stative or dynamic depending on the meaning.",
            "example": "I think he is right. / I am thinking about the problem."
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "1. Main groups",
    "intro": "Most verbs of state can be placed in a few common groups.",
    "items": [
        {
            "label": "Thinking / opinion",
            "title": "know, believe, understand, remember",
            "subtitle": "thought, knowledge, understanding"
        },
        {
            "label": "Possession",
            "title": "have, own, belong, need",
            "subtitle": "possession or belonging"
        },
        {
            "label": "Senses / perception",
            "title": "see, hear, smell, taste, seem",
            "subtitle": "perception or impression"
        },
        {
            "label": "Emotions / state",
            "title": "love, like, hate, want, prefer",
            "subtitle": "feelings, wants, states"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "2. When to use stative verbs",
    "sections": [
        {
            "label": "Thought and knowledge",
            "color": "emerald",
            "description": "For ideas, beliefs, memory, and understanding, we usually choose a <strong>simple form</strong>, not a continuous form.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "I know her name.",
                    "ua": "I know her name."
                },
                {
                    "en": "We believe you.",
                    "ua": "We believe you."
                },
                {
                    "en": "She understands the rule.",
                    "ua": "She understands the rule."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "label": "Possession and belonging",
            "color": "blue",
            "description": "When the verb shows that someone <strong>has</strong>, <strong>owns</strong>, or something <strong>belongs</strong> to someone, a continuous form is usually wrong.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "They own a small cafe.",
                    "ua": "They own a small cafe."
                },
                {
                    "en": "This bag belongs to me.",
                    "ua": "This bag belongs to me."
                },
                {
                    "en": "I need more time.",
                    "ua": "I need more time."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "label": "Perception and emotion",
            "color": "amber",
            "description": "Verbs of feeling, impression, and emotion also often behave as stative verbs.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "I see the problem now.",
                    "ua": "I see the problem now."
                },
                {
                    "en": "This soup tastes great.",
                    "ua": "This soup tastes great."
                },
                {
                    "en": "She loves jazz.",
                    "ua": "She loves jazz."
                }
            ]
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "3. When Continuous is possible",
    "sections": [
        {
            "label": "Meaning change",
            "color": "violet",
            "description": "Some verbs can take a <strong>different meaning</strong> in a continuous form and then become dynamic.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "I think he is right.",
                    "ua": "I think he is right."
                },
                {
                    "en": "I am thinking about our next trip.",
                    "ua": "I am thinking about our next trip."
                },
                {
                    "en": "She has a new laptop.",
                    "ua": "She has a new laptop."
                },
                {
                    "en": "She is having lunch.",
                    "ua": "She is having lunch."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "label": "Be careful with see / taste / smell",
            "color": "sky",
            "description": "If the meaning is general perception, the verb is often stative. If it is an active action, Continuous can be possible.",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "I see what you mean.",
                    "ua": "I see what you mean."
                },
                {
                    "en": "The chef is tasting the sauce.",
                    "ua": "The chef is tasting the sauce."
                },
                {
                    "en": "I smell smoke.",
                    "ua": "I smell smoke."
                }
            ],
            "note": "Ask yourself whether it is a state / impression or a real action in progress."
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "4. Common mistakes",
    "items": [
        {
            "label": "Mistake 1",
            "color": "rose",
            "title": "Using Continuous with a typical verb of state.",
            "wrong": "I am knowing the answer.",
            "right": "✅ <span class=\"font-mono\">I know the answer.</span>"
        },
        {
            "label": "Mistake 2",
            "color": "amber",
            "title": "Using Continuous with a feeling verb in its basic meaning.",
            "wrong": "She is loving jazz.",
            "right": "✅ <span class=\"font-mono\">She loves jazz.</span>"
        },
        {
            "label": "Mistake 3",
            "color": "sky",
            "title": "Missing the change of meaning.",
            "wrong": "I think about it now = I think he is right.",
            "right": "✅ <span class=\"font-mono\">I think he is right.</span> / <span class=\"font-mono\">I am thinking about it now.</span>"
        }
    ]
}

